00320     template<size_t operandBits, size_t shiftSignificantBits>
00321     WordType<operandBits> shift_semantics(X86InstructionKind kind, const WordType<operandBits> &operand,
00322                                           const WordType<operandBits> &source_bits, const WordType<8> &total_shift) {
00323         assert(x86_shr==kind || x86_sar==kind || x86_shl==kind || x86_shld==kind || x86_shrd==kind);
00324 
00325         // The 8086 does not mask the shift count; processors starting with the 80286 (including virtual-8086 mode) do
00326         // mask.  The effect (other than timing) is the same either way.
00327         WordType<shiftSignificantBits> maskedShiftCount = extract<0, shiftSignificantBits>(total_shift);
00328         WordType<1> isZeroShiftCount = policy.equalToZero(maskedShiftCount);
00329 
00330         // isLargeShift is true if the (unmasked) amount by which to shift is greater than or equal to the size in
00331         // bits of the destination operand.
00332         assert(shiftSignificantBits<8);
00333         WordType<1> isLargeShift = policy.invert(policy.equalToZero(extract<shiftSignificantBits, 8>(total_shift)));
00334 
00335         // isOneBitShift is true if the (masked) amount by which to shift is equal to one.
00336         uintmax_t m = ((uintmax_t)1 << shiftSignificantBits) - 1;
00337         WordType<shiftSignificantBits> mask = number<shiftSignificantBits>(m); // -1 in modulo arithmetic
00338         WordType<1> isOneBitShift = policy.equalToZero(policy.add(maskedShiftCount, mask));
00339 
00340         // Do the actual shift, according to instruction kind.
00341         WordType<operandBits> retval = undefined_<operandBits>(); // not all policies define a default c'tor
00342         switch (kind) {
00343             case x86_shr:
00344                 retval = policy.shiftRight(operand, maskedShiftCount);
00345                 break;
00346             case x86_sar:
00347                 retval = policy.shiftRightArithmetic(operand, maskedShiftCount);
00348                 break;
00349             case x86_shl:
00350                 retval = policy.shiftLeft(operand, maskedShiftCount);
00351                 break;
00352             case x86_shrd:
00353                 retval = policy.ite(isLargeShift,
00354                                     undefined_<operandBits>(),
00355                                     policy.or_(policy.shiftRight(operand, maskedShiftCount),
00356                                                policy.ite(isZeroShiftCount,
00357                                                           number<operandBits>(0),
00358                                                           policy.shiftLeft(source_bits, policy.negate(maskedShiftCount)))));
00359                 break;
00360             case x86_shld:
00361                 retval = policy.ite(isLargeShift,
00362                                     undefined_<operandBits>(),
00363                                     policy.or_(policy.shiftLeft(operand, maskedShiftCount),
00364                                                policy.ite(isZeroShiftCount,
00365                                                           number<operandBits>(0),
00366                                                           policy.shiftRight(source_bits, policy.negate(maskedShiftCount)))));
00367                 break;
00368             default:
00369                 abort();
00370         }
00371 
00372         // The AF flag is undefined if a shift occurs.  The documentation for SHL, SHR, and SAR are somewhat ambiguous about
00373         // this, but the documentation for SHLD and SHRD is more specific.  We assume that both sets of shift instructions
00374         // behave the same way.
00375         writeRegister(REG_AF, policy.ite(isZeroShiftCount, readRegister<1>(REG_AF), undefined_<1>()));
00376 
00377         // What is the last bit shifted off the operand?  If we're right shifting by N bits, then the original operand N-1 bit
00378         // is what should make it into the final CF; if we're left shifting by N bits then we need bit operandBits-N.
00379         WordType<shiftSignificantBits> bitPosition;
00380         if (x86_shr==kind || x86_sar==kind) {
00381             bitPosition = policy.add(maskedShiftCount, mask);
00382         } else {
00383             bitPosition = policy.add(number<shiftSignificantBits>(operandBits & m), // probably zero in modulo arithmetic
00384                                      policy.add(policy.invert(maskedShiftCount),
00385                                                 number<shiftSignificantBits>(1)));
00386         }
00387         WordType<1> shifted_off = extract<0, 1>(policy.shiftRight(operand, bitPosition));
00388 
00389         // New carry flag value.  From the Intel manual, the CF flag is "undefined for SHL and SHR [and SAL] instructions where
00390         // the count is greater than or equal to the size (in bits) of the destination operand", and "if the count is 0, the
00391         // flags are not affected."  The manual is silent about the value of CF for large SAR shifts, so we use the original
00392         // sign bit, matching the pseudo-code in the manual.
00393         WordType<1> newCF = policy.ite(isZeroShiftCount,
00394                                         readRegister<1>(REG_CF), // preserve current value
00395                                         policy.ite(isLargeShift,
00396                                                    (x86_sar==kind ?
00397                                                     extract<operandBits-1, operandBits>(operand) : // original sign bit
00398                                                     undefined_<1>()),
00399                                                    shifted_off));
00400         writeRegister(REG_CF, newCF);
00401 
00402         // Ajust the overflow flag.  From the Intel manual for the SHL, SHR, and SAR instructions, "The OF flag is affected
00403         // only on 1-bit shifts.  For left shifts, the OF flag is set to 0 if the most-significant bit of the result is the
00404         // same as the CF flag (that is, the top two bits of the original operand were the same); otherwise, it is set to 1.
00405         // For the SAR instruction, the OF flag is cleared for all 1-bit shifts.  For the SHR instruction, the OF flag is set
00406         // to the most-significant bit of the original operand."  Later, it states that "the OF flag is affected only for 1-bit
00407         // shifts; otherwise it is undefined."  We're assuming that the statement "if the count is 0, then the flags are not
00408         // affected" takes precedence. For SHLD and SHRD it says, "for a 1-bit shift, the OF flag is set if a sign changed
00409         // occurred; otherwise it is cleared. For shifts greater than 1 bit, the OF flag is undefined."
00410         WordType<1> newOF = undefined_<1>();
00411         switch (kind) {
00412             case x86_shr:
00413                 newOF = policy.ite(isOneBitShift,
00414                                    extract<operandBits-1, operandBits>(operand),
00415                                    policy.ite(isZeroShiftCount, 
00416                                               readRegister<1>(REG_OF),
00417                                               undefined_<1>()));
00418                 break;
00419             case x86_sar:
00420                 newOF = policy.ite(isOneBitShift,
00421                                    policy.false_(),
00422                                    policy.ite(isZeroShiftCount,
00423                                               readRegister<1>(REG_OF),
00424                                               undefined_<1>()));
00425                 break;
00426             case x86_shl:
00427             case x86_shld:
00428             case x86_shrd:
00429                 newOF = policy.ite(isOneBitShift,
00430                                    policy.xor_(newCF, extract<operandBits-1, operandBits>(retval)),
00431                                    policy.ite(isZeroShiftCount,
00432                                               readRegister<1>(REG_OF),
00433                                               undefined_<1>()));
00434                 break;
00435             default: // to shut up compiler warnings even though we would have aborted by now.
00436                 abort();
00437         }
00438         writeRegister(REG_OF, newOF);
00439 
00440         // Result flags SF, ZF, and PF are set according to the result, but are unchanged if the shift count is zero.
00441         setFlagsForResult<operandBits>(retval, policy.invert(isZeroShiftCount));
00442         return retval;
00443     }

00503     /* Returns an eight-bit value desribed by an instruction operand. */
00504     Word(8) read8(SgAsmExpression* e) {
00505         switch (e->variantT()) {
00506             case V_SgAsmx86RegisterReferenceExpression: {
00507                 SgAsmx86RegisterReferenceExpression* rre = isSgAsmx86RegisterReferenceExpression(e);
00508                 return policy.readRegister<8>(rre->get_descriptor());
00509             }
00510             case V_SgAsmBinaryAdd: {
00511                 return policy.add(read8(isSgAsmBinaryAdd(e)->get_lhs()), read8(isSgAsmBinaryAdd(e)->get_rhs()));
00512             }
00513             case V_SgAsmBinaryMultiply: {
00514                 SgAsmByteValueExpression* rhs = isSgAsmByteValueExpression(isSgAsmBinaryMultiply(e)->get_rhs());
00515                 if (!rhs)
00516                     throw Exception("byte value expression expected", current_instruction);
00517                 SgAsmExpression* lhs = isSgAsmBinaryMultiply(e)->get_lhs();
00518                 return extract<0, 8>(policy.unsignedMultiply(read8(lhs), read8(rhs)));
00519             }
00520             case V_SgAsmMemoryReferenceExpression: {
00521                 return readMemory<8>(getSegregFromMemoryReference(isSgAsmMemoryReferenceExpression(e)),
00522                                      readEffectiveAddress(e), policy.true_());
00523             }
00524             case V_SgAsmByteValueExpression:
00525             case V_SgAsmWordValueExpression:
00526             case V_SgAsmDoubleWordValueExpression:
00527             case V_SgAsmQuadWordValueExpression: {

00668     /* Returns true if W has an even number of bits set; false for an odd number */
00669     Word(1) parity(Word(8) w) {
00670         Word(1) p01 = policy.xor_(extract<0, 1>(w), extract<1, 2>(w));
00671         Word(1) p23 = policy.xor_(extract<2, 3>(w), extract<3, 4>(w));
00672         Word(1) p45 = policy.xor_(extract<4, 5>(w), extract<5, 6>(w));
00673         Word(1) p67 = policy.xor_(extract<6, 7>(w), extract<7, 8>(w));
00674         Word(1) p0123 = policy.xor_(p01, p23);
00675         Word(1) p4567 = policy.xor_(p45, p67);
00676         Word(1) pall = policy.xor_(p0123, p4567);
00677         return policy.invert(pall);
00678     }

00680     /* Sets flags: parity, sign, and zero */
00681     template <size_t Len>
00682     void setFlagsForResult(const Word(Len)& result) {
00683         writeRegister(REG_PF, parity(extract<0, 8>(result)));
00684         writeRegister(REG_SF, extract<Len - 1, Len>(result));
00685         writeRegister(REG_ZF, policy.equalToZero(result));
00686     }

00688     /* Sets flags conditionally. Sets parity, sign, and zero flags if COND is true. */
00689     template <size_t Len>
00690     void setFlagsForResult(const Word(Len)& result, Word(1) cond) {
00691         writeRegister(REG_PF, policy.ite(cond, parity(extract<0, 8>(result)), readRegister<1>(REG_PF)));
00692         writeRegister(REG_SF, policy.ite(cond, extract<Len - 1, Len>(result), readRegister<1>(REG_SF)));
00693         writeRegister(REG_ZF, policy.ite(cond, policy.equalToZero(result), readRegister<1>(REG_ZF)));
00694     }

00696     /* Adds A and B and adjusts condition flags. Can be used for subtraction if B is two's complement and invertCarries is set. */
00697     template <size_t Len>
00698     Word(Len) doAddOperation(const Word(Len)& a, const Word(Len)& b, bool invertCarries, Word(1) carryIn) {
00699         Word(Len) carries = number<Len>(0);
00700         Word(Len) result = policy.addWithCarries(a, b, invertMaybe(carryIn, invertCarries), carries/*out*/);
00701         setFlagsForResult<Len>(result);
00702         writeRegister(REG_AF, invertMaybe(extract<3, 4>(carries), invertCarries));
00703         writeRegister(REG_CF, invertMaybe(extract<Len - 1, Len>(carries), invertCarries));
00704         writeRegister(REG_OF, policy.xor_(extract<Len - 1, Len>(carries), extract<Len - 2, Len - 1>(carries)));
00705         return result;
00706     }
00707 
00708     /* Conditionally adds A and B and adjusts condition flags. Can be used for subtraction if B is two's complement and
00709      * invertCarries is set. Does nothing if COND is false. */ 
00710     template <size_t Len>
00711     Word(Len) doAddOperation(const Word(Len)& a, const Word(Len)& b, bool invertCarries, Word(1) carryIn, Word(1) cond) {
00712         Word(Len) carries = number<Len>(0);
00713         Word(Len) result = policy.addWithCarries(a, b, invertMaybe(carryIn, invertCarries), carries/*out*/);
00714         setFlagsForResult<Len>(result, cond);
00715         writeRegister(REG_AF,
00716                       policy.ite(cond,
00717                                  invertMaybe(extract<3, 4>(carries), invertCarries),
00718                                  readRegister<1>(REG_AF)));
00719         writeRegister(REG_CF,
00720                       policy.ite(cond,
00721                                  invertMaybe(extract<Len - 1, Len>(carries), invertCarries),
00722                                  readRegister<1>(REG_CF)));
00723         writeRegister(REG_OF,
00724                       policy.ite(cond,
00725                                  policy.xor_(extract<Len - 1, Len>(carries), extract<Len - 2, Len - 1>(carries)),
00726                                  readRegister<1>(REG_OF)));
00727         return result;
00728     }

00730     /* Does increment (decrement with DEC set), and adjusts condition flags. */
00731     template <size_t Len>
00732     Word(Len) doIncOperation(const Word(Len)& a, bool dec, bool setCarry) {
00733         Word(Len) carries = number<Len>(0);
00734         Word(Len) result = policy.addWithCarries(a, number<Len>(dec ? -1 : 1), policy.false_(), carries/*out*/);
00735         setFlagsForResult<Len>(result);
00736         writeRegister(REG_AF, invertMaybe(extract<3, 4>(carries), dec));
00737         writeRegister(REG_OF, policy.xor_(extract<Len - 1, Len>(carries), extract<Len - 2, Len - 1>(carries)));
00738         if (setCarry)
00739             writeRegister(REG_CF, invertMaybe(extract<Len - 1, Len>(carries), dec));
00740         return result;
00741     }

02525     void processBlock(SgAsmBlock* b) {
02526         const SgAsmStatementPtrList& stmts = b->get_statementList();
02527         if (stmts.empty()) return;
02528         if (!isSgAsmInstruction(stmts[0])) return; /* A block containing functions or something */
02529         size_t i = 0;
02530         while (i < stmts.size()) {
02531             size_t oldI = i;
02532             /* Advance until either i points to a repeated string op or it is just after a hlt or int */
02533             while (i < stmts.size() && !isRepeatedStringOp(stmts[i]) && (i == oldI || !isHltOrInt(stmts[i - 1]))) ++i;
02534             processBlock(stmts, oldI, i);
02535             if (i >= stmts.size()) break;
02536             if (isRepeatedStringOp(stmts[i])) {
02537                 processBlock(stmts, i, i + 1);
02538                 ++i;
02539             }
02540             ROSE_ASSERT(i != oldI);
02541         }
02542     }
